<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;has been recently identified.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains information about the work you are citing, including the newspaper title and publication date.
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
Footnotes are placed in numerical order at the bottom of the page. When the author is anonymous, begin the footnote with the name of the article followed by the name of the newspaper (Example A).
<br><br>
When references to the same work follow each other with no other references in&#45;between, replace the title and publication details with <strong>ibid</strong>. (Example B). Page numbers are not usually given.
<br><br>
<strong>Example A</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">1. &#34;Professor to Talk Rubbish at Next Senate Meeting,&#34; <em>Herald Tribune</em>, December 15, 2056.</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example B</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">7. Ibid.</span>
</blockquote>
